2005-02-25 08:30 UTC+0700 Andi Jahja <xharbour@cbn.net.id>
  * source/vm/fm.c
    ! define HB_FM_WIN32_ALLOC when building DLL. This ensures consistent
      memory management because programs will use the system's one.
      Now, for a test case, I have tested thoroughly the interchangeability
      among Borland's harbour.dll and MSVC's one. Without defining this one,
      hb_xgrab always fail in allocating memory when a BCC program access
      MSVC DLL and vice versa. Now the symptom has gone.
      Please test with a complex program (xbscript.prg will do), before and
      after this change. The benefit is obvious. Note : in order to have the
      interchangeability, we have to compile MSVC DLL with additional
      HB_FUNC_NO_DECORATION flag, else DLL will have mangled symbols which
      are impossible to access from BCC programs.

